INSERT INTO `wp_commentmeta` VALUES (3629, 1179, 'akismet_as_submitted', 'a:56:{s:15:"comment_post_ID";s:4:"1310";s:14:"comment_author";s:5:"Akira";s:20:"comment_author_email";s:25:"pedro.almeida@bbcr.com.br";s:18:"comment_author_url";s:54:"http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100003406008797";s:15:"comment_content";s:1328:"< What the finders found >Vanilla, often coesedirnd the  plain Jane  ice cream flavor, actually has a very exotic origin! Vanilla extract is derived from the seed pods of . After a lengthy process of curing and fermentation,  (often called  beans  because of their resemblance to string beans) are dried, and then, usually with alcohol, an extract is made.Vanilla adds a delicious aroma and taste to many foods, including ice cream and baked goods. If you want to know more about the nature of the stuff, check out the book,  by Ken Cameron.Homemade vanilla extractMaking your own homemade vanilla extract is quite simple   you need the vanilla seed pods and a liquor, such as vodka.Cheri Sicard of  suggests this technique:You need:2 vanilla beans, cut lengthwise3/4 cup vodkaPut the vanilla beans in a small half-pint jar and cover with vodka. Set aside to steep for 3-4 weeks. Keeping the beans in the jar, you may use this homemade blend like any other vanilla extract. When the liquid gets below the beans, just add more vodka.Cheri notes that you can usually get three or four bottles of extract from the two vanilla beans. If you choose, add sugar to the extract to soften the flavor of the alcohol.This answer was adapted from an article Mrs FF wrote for ChefMom.com in January 2001, which is no longer online.Photo bya0";s:12:"comment_type";s:0:"";s:14:"comment_parent";s:1:"0";s:7:"user_ID";s:1:"0";s:7:"user_ip";s:14:"188.143.232.12";s:10:"user_agent";s:90:"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.0.5) Gecko/2008120122 Firefox/3.0.5";s:8:"referrer";s:54:"http://www.zythepsary.com/techie/weekend-of-webmaking/";s:4:"blog";s:25:"http://www.zythepsary.com";s:9:"blog_lang";s:5:"en_US";s:12:"blog_charset";s:5:"UTF-8";s:9:"permalink";s:54:"http://www.zythepsary.com/techie/weekend-of-webmaking/";s:21:"akismet_comment_nonce";s:6:"passed";s:11:"POST_author";s:5:"Akira";s:10:"POST_email";s:25:"pedro.almeida@bbcr.com.br";s:8:"POST_url";s:54:"http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100003406008797";s:12:"POST_comment";s:1328:"< What the finders found >Vanilla, often coesedirnd the  plain Jane  ice cream flavor, actually has a very exotic origin! Vanilla extract is derived from the seed pods of . After a lengthy process of curing and fermentation,  (often called  beans  because of their resemblance to string beans) are dried, and then, usually with alcohol, an extract is made.Vanilla adds a delicious aroma and taste to many foods, including ice cream and baked goods. If you want to know more about the nature of the stuff, check out the book,  by Ken Cameron.Homemade vanilla extractMaking your own homemade vanilla extract is quite simple   you need the vanilla seed pods and a liquor, such as vodka.Cheri Sicard of  suggests this technique:You need:2 vanilla beans, cut lengthwise3/4 cup vodkaPut the vanilla beans in a small half-pint jar and cover with vodka. Set aside to steep for 3-4 weeks. Keeping the beans in the jar, you may use this homemade blend like any other vanilla extract. When the liquid gets below the beans, just add more vodka.Cheri notes that you can usually get three or four bottles of extract from the two vanilla beans. If you choose, add sugar to the extract to soften the flavor of the alcohol.This answer was adapted from an article Mrs FF wrote for ChefMom.com in January 2001, which is no longer online.Photo bya0";s:11:"POST_submit";s:12:"Post Comment";s:20:"POST_comment_post_ID";s:4:"1310";s:19:"POST_comment_parent";s:1:"0";s:26:"POST_akismet_comment_nonce";s:10:"296c26a0cf";s:26:"POST_Zythepsary_var_thanks";s:6:"thanks";s:25:"POST_Zythepsary_var_sorry";s:8:"BTbhIBYX";s:15:"SERVER_SOFTWARE";s:8:"Apach